    Satya Soleil

    Here is some things to remember when devising your meeting with Romeo's mother: I hope that you can appreciate this means of getting someone to do what you want.

    1) Describe: Describe the situation. Stick to the facts. "I have noticed that you do not ride safely on a bike with Romeo."

    2) Express: Express your feelings using "I" statements. ("I feel..." "I would like..."). Do not assume the other person knows how you feel. Stay away from "you should". Try not to overstate your emotions. "When I see Romeo on a bike in a seat too small for him without a helmet, I feel worried about his safety."

    3) Assert: Ask for what you want or say "no" clearly. Remember the other person cannot read your mind. "I would like have him in my care more often based on some of these things that I feel compromise his safety and well being." No threats, manipulation or aggression.

    4) Reinforce: Reward (reinforce) the person ahead of time by explaining the positive effects of getting what you want. Also, reward her afterwards. "This compromise relieves you of having to worry so much about meeting his needs when it is clear that it may not be within your means to do so effectively."

    5) Mindful: Keep your focus on what you want, avoiding distractions. Come back to your assertion again and again like a broken record. IGNORE ATTACKS and keep making your point. Stay with the one topic. No need to throw in the entire "kitchen sink".

    6) Appear Confident: Make and maintain eye contact. Use a confident tone of voice - do not whisper, mumble or give up and say "whatever".

    7) Negotiate: Be willing to GIVE TO GET. Ask for her input. Offer alternative solutions to the problem. Know when to agree to disagree and walk away. Use the wild card when necessary: Ask, "What would you do in my situation?"

    D = Describe E = Express A = Assert R = Reinforce
